{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 14:21:08.539253", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Codes: K - kernel route, C - connected, S - static, R - RIP,\\n       O - OSPF, I - IS-IS, B - BGP, E - EIGRP, N - NHRP,\\n       T - Table, v - VNC, V - VNC-Direct, A - Babel, F - PBR,\\n       f - OpenFabric,\\n       > - selected route, * - FIB route, q - queued, r - rejected, b - backup\\n       t - trapped, o - offload failure\\n\\nR>* 10.0.0.0/24 [120/3] via 192.168.0.17, eth0, weight 1, 00:00:50\\nR>* 10.0.1.0/24 [120/3] via 192.168.0.17, eth0, weight 1, 00:00:45\\nR>* 10.0.2.0/24 [120/4] via 192.168.0.17, eth0, weight 1, 00:00:45\\nR>* 10.0.3.0/24 [120/4] via 192.168.0.17, eth0, weight 1, 00:00:45\\nC>* 20.0.0.0/24 is directly connected, br0, 00:00:51\\nR>* 20.0.1.0/24 [120/3] via 192.168.0.17, eth0, weight 1, 00:00:45\\nR>* 192.168.0.0/31 [120/3] via 192.168.0.17, eth0, weight 1, 00:00:50\\nR>* 192.168.0.2/31 [120/3] via 192.168.0.17, eth0, weight 1, 00:00:50\\nR>* 192.168.0.4/31 [120/3] via 192.168.0.17, eth0, weight 1, 00:00:50\\nR>* 192.168.0.6/31 [120/3] via 192.168.0.17, eth0, weight 1, 00:00:45\\nR>* 192.168.0.8/31 [120/3] via 192.168.0.17, eth0, weight 1, 00:00:45\\nR>* 192.168.0.10/31 [120/4] via 192.168.0.17, eth0, weight 1, 00:00:45\\nR>* 192.168.0.12/31 [120/2] via 192.168.0.17, eth0, weight 1, 00:00:50\\nR>* 192.168.0.14/31 [120/2] via 192.168.0.17, eth0, weight 1, 00:00:50\\nC>* 192.168.0.16/31 is directly connected, eth0, 00:00:51\\nR>* 192.168.0.18/31 [120/2] via 192.168.0.17, eth0, weight 1, 00:00:50' name='frr_show_ip_route' id='e151ac15-6dda-4ddd-aff3-1eec4e627c1c' tool_call_id='call_XxdqrYBcR19Yje2O5DHUqM8B'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 14:22:08.222439", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Diagnostic Report — RIP mini-Internet with VPN overlay\nDate: (current capture)\n\nExecutive summary\n- The network is operational: IP forwarding and RIP are converged and all hosts/servers can ping each other (0% loss in the provided reachability matrix).\n- However there is a clear policy/architecture anomaly: the external web LAN 20.0.0.0/24 is being advertised and reachable across the RIP infrastructure, so the web servers that were intended to be accessible only via the WireGuard VPN are reachable directly from internal hosts. At the same time the WireGuard interfaces on the VPN endpoints show no traffic, indicating the VPN overlay is not carrying user traffic.\n- Primary devices implicated: external_router_1 (advertising the 20.0.0.0/24 prefix into RIP), gateway_router (odd FRR configuration entry), and the WireGuard endpoints (host_1 and vpn_server_1) which show no WG traffic.\n- Probable root cause: routing misconfiguration / incorrect prefix advertisement (20.0.0.0/24) into RIP (so traffic to the external web LAN flows over the base network rather than through the VPN). WireGuard traffic is not being used / no handshake observed on wg interfaces.\n\nDetailed findings and evidence\n\n1) Overall connectivity and routing health\n- Full-mesh RIP appears converged. The reachability results show all tested src→dst pairs succeeded with 0% loss (get_reachability).\n- FRR route tables on each router show learned RIP routes for the 10.0.0.0/24 internal LANs and 20.0.0.0/24 external LANs (R entries for 20.0.0.0/24 present in router1, router2, gateway_router, external_router_1).\n  - Example: router1 has \"R>* 20.0.0.0/24 [120/3] via 192.168.0.13, eth3\" (frr_show_ip_route).\n- Interfaces on routers and servers are UP; counters show traffic passed on many interfaces (ifconfig outputs).\n\n2) WireGuard state (VPN overlay)\n- host_1:\n  - wg0 exists and is UP with IP 172.16.1.11/24, but the wg0 interface shows RX packets 0 TX packets 0 (ifconfig output).\n  - host_1 routing includes 172.16.1.0/24 via wg0 but default route is via 10.0.0.1.\n- vpn_server_1:\n  - wg0 exists and is UP with IP 172.16.1.1/24, but wg0 shows RX/TX 0 as well.\n- Interpretation: the WG interfaces are present and up, but there is no observed WireGuard packet exchange in the capture. Either the tunnel is not established (no handshake) or no traffic is routed via the tunnel during measurements.\n\n3) Policy/architecture anomaly: web servers reachable without VPN\n- The network description stated that web_server_1_1 and web_server_1_2 are intended to be accessible only via the VPN overlay. However:\n  - The reachability matrix shows internal hosts (host_1, host_2, host_3, host_4, etc.) can directly ping 20.0.0.3 and 20.0.0.4 (web_server_1_1 and web_server_1_2) with low RTTs and 0% packet loss.\n  - FRR on external_router_1 advertises 20.0.0.0/24 into RIP (frr_show_running_config: \"network 20.0.0.0/24\"; frr_show_ip_route shows the prefix as connected on br0).\n  - Gateway_router and the internal FRR routers have RIP-learned routes to 20.0.0.0/24 (so traffic to 20.0.0.0/24 flows via the IP infrastructure).\n- Conclusion: The intended isolation (only reachable via the WG) is not enforced because the 20.0.0.0/24 prefix is propagated into the routing plane and is reachable via the base network.\n\n4) Configuration oddities / possible misconfigurations\n- gateway_router FRR config shows: \"network 192.168.0.0/16\" and \"network None\" in the running config (frr_show_running_config). \"network None\" is abnormal (likely a configuration error or a placeholder that was accidentally saved). Despite this, RIP is operating and routes are present. This entry should be flagged as a misconfiguration.\n- external_router_1 has br0 (bridge) with 20.0.0.1 and the FRR config advertises the 20.0.0.0/24 network via RIP. If the design requirement was to keep that LAN reachable only via WG, advertising it into RIP is incorrect.\n- WireGuard endpoints show interfaces present but zero packet counters — either WG peers are not configured/handshakes are not occurring or traffic is not being forced over the tunnel because routing prefers infrastructure paths.\n\n5) Minor operational anomalies\n- external_router_1 eth3: RX dropped count = 1 (ifconfig shows \"RX dropped 1\"). Single dropped packet observed — minor.\n- Some RTT variability observed in one path: web_server_1_2 → vpn_server_1 showed high rtt_mdev (3.788ms) and max 9.738ms in the ping sample. That is an outlier but connectivity remains functional.\n\nFault localization (devices or subsystems likely at fault)\n- external_router_1\n  - Reason: It is the device connected to the 20.0.0.0/24 LAN (br0 = 20.0.0.1) and its FRR config contains \"network 20.0.0.0/24\" — the router is advertising the web LAN into RIP, producing direct reachability outside the VPN.\n- gateway_router\n  - Reason: FRR running-config includes \"network None\" (misconfiguration) and route table shows it is propagating/receiving the 20.0.0.0/24 route via RIP. It participates in distributing the external LAN prefix across the internal routers.\n- WireGuard endpoints host_1 and vpn_server_1 (the overlay subsystem)\n  - Reason: wg0 interfaces are present but show zero packet counters — the overlay is not carrying traffic as intended (no observed WG packet exchange during the capture). This makes the overlay ineffective even if it was intended to be the only path to the web servers.\n\nProbable root cause(s)\n- Primary root cause: Inadvertent advertisement of the external web LAN (20.0.0.0/24) into the baseline routing protocol (RIP). Because 20.0.0.0/24 is learned and reachable via RIP, internal hosts route directly over the infrastructure to the web servers, bypassing the intended VPN-only access path.\n- Secondary root cause / contributing: WireGuard overlay is not being used (wg0 shows zero packets), either because the WireGuard session is not established or because routing/advertisement makes the overlay unnecessary. Additionally, gateway_router has a suspicious FRR \"network None\" entry — a sign of configuration issues which could have contributed to incorrect network advertisement/policy.\n\nImpact\n- Security/policy: The intended access control (web servers only accessible via VPN) is not being enforced — internal hosts can access those services directly.\n- Operational: No immediate connectivity outages; RIP and forwarding are functional. However the overlay is effectively unused which undermines the intended architecture.\n- Visibility: WireGuard not carrying traffic — there may be no auditing or control of traffic to the web servers via the secure tunnel.\n\nRelevant evidence excerpts (selected)\n- WireGuard interfaces:\n  - host_1 wg0: \"inet 172.16.1.11 ... RX packets 0 ... TX packets 0\"\n  - vpn_server_1 wg0: \"inet 172.16.1.1 ... RX packets 0 ... TX packets 0\"\n- FRR configs:\n  - external_router_1 running-config: \"router rip ... network 192.168.0.0/16 ... network 20.0.0.0/24\"\n  - gateway_router running-config: \"router rip ... network 192.168.0.0/16 ... network None\"\n- Routes:\n  - router1 ip_route includes: \"R>* 20.0.0.0/24 [120/3] via 192.168.0.13, eth3\"\n  - gateway_router ip_route includes: \"20.0.0.0/24 dev br0 proto kernel scope link src 20.0.0.1\"\n- Reachability:\n  - get_reachability: host_1 → web_server_1_1 (20.0.0.3) TX 4 RX 4 loss 0.0.\n\nSummary / conclusions (no remediation included)\n- The network's control plane and forwarding plane are functional and RIP has converged, but the architecture's access-policy goal is violated: the external web LAN is advertised into the routed fabric and is reachable without using the VPN overlay.\n- WireGuard endpoints are present but show no packet exchange; the overlay is not actively carrying user traffic in the captured state.\n- Devices most relevant to this anomaly are external_router_1 (advertising 20.0.0.0/24) and gateway_router (contains an abnormal \"network None\" FRR entry and participates in propagating the external prefix). The WG subsystem (host_1 and vpn_server_1) shows no active tunnel traffic.\n- Root cause: misadvertisement of the 20.0.0.0/24 network into RIP (plus inactive/unused WireGuard tunnel).\n\nIf you want, I can next:\n- Show the full FRR RIP neighbor and RIP route advertisements, or\n- Capture WireGuard status (lw or wg show) to confirm handshake state, or\n- Trace a packet path (tcpdump) to show which path to 20.0.0.3 is used (tunnel vs infrastructure).\n(These actions would be diagnostic follow-ups. No remediation will be proposed unless requested.)", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 23534, "output_tokens": 4641, "total_tokens": 28175, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 9856}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2496}}}
